SIMPLE: elective
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Elective
<hw>E*lect"ive</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>⟦eacute⟧lectif</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Exerting the power of
choice; selecting; <as>as, an <ex>elective</ex> act</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Pertaining to, or consisting in, choice, or right of
choosing; electoral.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The independent use of their <qex>elective</qex> franchise.</q>
<rj><qau>Bancroft.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Bestowed or passing by election; <as>as, an
<ex>elective</ex> office.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Kings of Rome were at first <qex>elective</qex>; . . . for such
are the conditions of an <qex>elective</qex> kingdom.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Dependent on choice; that can be refused; <as>as, an
<ex>elective</ex> college course</as>. Opposite of <ant>required</ant>
or <ant>mandatory</ant>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Elective affinity</b></col> <it>or</it>
<col><b>Elective attraction</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Chem.)</fld>, <cd>a
tendency to unite with certain things; chemism.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Elective</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Elective
<hw>E*lect"ive</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>In an American college, an
optional study or course of study; a course that is not required.</def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Electively</ent>⟦br⟧
